{"id":"2211.06498","submitter":"James Hague","authors":"G. D. Adebanjo, J. P. Hague and P. E. Kornilovitch","title":"Ubiquity of light small pairs in Hubbard models with long range hoppings\n  and interactions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we examine how next-nearest neighbor hopping and interaction\naffect pair properties, concluding that small and light (superlight) pairs are\nubiquitous in dilute extended Hubbard models with next-nearest neighbor\ninteractions and hopping. We are motivated by two unconventional\nsuperconductors, the cuprates and fullerides, which are expected to have\nnext-nearest neighbor hopping and interactions. We determine pair properties\nfor a dilute extended Hubbard model with large Hubbard $U$ and both near- and\nnext-nearest neighbor hopping and attraction, on a range of lattices using both\nnumerical and analytical approaches. We find that the presence of next-nearest\nneighbor hopping, $t'$ and near- and next-nearest neighbor attraction ($V$ and\n$V'$) very significantly lowers the pair mass in a wide range of lattices. The\npair mass decreases with increased $t'$ and $V'$ (where it has a minimum when\n$V'=V$). Transition temperatures are estimated for the Bose-Einstein\ncondensation of pairs leading to superconductivity. The presence of both $t'$\nand $V'$ leads ubiquitously to small strongly bound pairs with an inverse mass\nthat is linear in hopping, which could lead to high temperature BECs. We\nbriefly discuss potential implications for unconventional superconductors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 11 Nov 2022 22:22:16 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 7 Jun 2023 11:07:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-06-08"}
